California law gives parties of interest one year from the date the tax sale deed is recorded to file a claim. Claims are filed directly with the county Tax Collector, not with a court. If you owned the property at the time of sale, or held a qualifying recorded interest such as a mortgage or lien, you may be entitled to some or all of the remaining funds.

The county will typically ask for documentation showing your right to claim, such as a deed, title report, or probate order. If the former owner is deceased, most counties require a certified copy of Letters Testamentary or Letters of Administration before releasing funds to an estate representative.

If you choose to work with someone to help file the claim, California Business and Professions Code Section 6148 requires written fee agreements for attorneys. For non-attorney recovery agents, the fee should be clearly stated as a percentage or other compensation method before you sign any assignment or authorization. There is no specific statutory cap on recovery fees for tax-sale excess-proceeds claims in California.

We can review the county records with you and explain what documentation is typically required for {{ county_name }} County. This letter is informational only and is not legal advice.

